characteristic: The crossing of the Great St. Bernard Pass remains a legendary episode of the Napoleonic epic. Although many Swiss passes were crossed by French, Russian, and Austrian armies in 1799 and 1800, only the Great St. Bernard has been remembered by history, thanks to the painter David.
The Battle of Rivoli (14–15 January 1797) was a key victory in the first Italian campaign of Napoleon Bonaparte, consolidating the French success in northern Italy.
The Siege of Jaffa was fought from 3 to 7 March 1799 between France and the Ottoman Empire. The French were led by Napoleon Bonaparte, and they captured the city.

François Rabelais (born between 1483 and 1494, died 1553) was a French Renaissance writer, physician, Renaissance humanist, monk and Greek scholar. He is primarily known as a writer of satire, the grotesque, bawdy jokes, and songs.

Bernard Germain Étienne de Laville-sur-Illon, comte de Lacépède (26 December 1756 – 6 October 1825), was a French zoologist and politician. A friend of Buffon, he authored the significant "Histoire naturelle des poissons" (Natural History of Fish, 1798-1803), which had a major impact on ichthyology.
Justin-Bonaventure Morard de Galles (30 March 1741 – 21 July 1809) was a French admiral.
Joséphine de Beauharnais (23 June 1763 – 29 May 1814) was the first wife of Napoleon I, and thus the first Empress of the French.
Jean le Rond d'Alembert (16 November 1717 – 29 October 1783) was a French mathematician, philosopher, and encyclopaedist.
Jean-Baptiste Colbert (29 August 1619 – 6 September 1683) was a French statesman who served as Controller-General of Finances from 1665 to 1683 under the rule of King Louis XIV.
Charles-Pierre Claret de Fleurieu (2 July 1738 – 18 August 1810) was a French explorer, hydrographer and politician. He served as Minister of the Navy and the Colonies.

Sébastien Le Prestre de Vauban (1633–1707), was a French military engineer who served under Louis XIV. He is generally considered the greatest engineer of his time, and one of the most important in Western military history.

Jean-Jacques-Régis de Cambacérès (18 October 1753 – 8 March 1824) was appointed Prince-Archchancellor upon the proclamation of the First Empire in 1804. He presided over the Senate and the Council of State during the emperor's travels.
Jean-Baptiste-Joseph Willart de Grécourt (7 February 1684 – 2 April 1743) was a French poet.

ausEName: Sir Joseph Banks Group Conservation Park
characteristic: The Treaty of Leoben was a peace treaty signed on 17 April 1797 by Napoleon Bonaparte.
Jean-Baptiste de Nompère de Champagny, duc de Cadore (4 August 1756 – 3 July 1834), was a French soldier and politician.
Joseph-Louis Lagrange (25 January 1736 – 10 April 1813) was an Italian-born, naturalised French mathematician, physicist, and astronomer. He spent much of his career in Berlin and Paris.
Lazare Carnot (1753-1823) was a French politician, engineer, and mathematician. He was a leading figure in the French Revolution and the Napoleonic Wars, and was made a Count of the Empire.
Antoine-Laurent de Jussieu (12 April 1748 – 17 September 1836) was a French botanist.
Louis-Nicolas Vauquelin (16 May 1763 – 14 November 1829) was a French pharmacist and chemist. He discovered two chemical elements, chromium and beryllium.

ausEName: baie Delambre, Coffin Bay, Port Douglas
characteristic: Jean-Baptiste Joseph Delambre (19 September 1749 – 19 August 1822) was a French astronomer and mathematician.

François Alexandre Frédéric, duc de La Rochefoucauld-Liancourt (11 January 1747 – 27 March 1827), was the founder of an institution that gave rise to the Arts et Métiers schools, and a promoter of mutual instruction in France.
Antoine François, comte d'Andréossy (6 March 1761 – 10 September 1828), was a French general of the Empire, hydrographer, and diplomat.
Antoine-Jean-Marie Thévenard (7 December 1733 – 9 February 1815) was a French naval officer and politician. He ended his career with the rank of vice-admiral.
Joachim Murat (25 March 1767 – 13 October 1815) was a Marshal of the Empire, Grand Duke of Berg and Cleves, and later King of Naples.
